 old Soviet republic was common on the 60-80s. Mostly of them have been proved to be of related genera, but not Agathis.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[Dicksonia]]?<ref name=Plant1></ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Dicksonia bulbacea?''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Various Locations\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMicroparts of leafs and assigned Pollen.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Dicksoniaceae]]. Probably a mistaken tree Fern.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[Onychium]]?<ref name=Plant1></ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Onychium baccatum?''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Various Locations\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMicroparts of leafs and assigned Pollen.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Pteridoideae]]. Maybe a relative genus\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[Lygodium]]?<ref name=Plant1></ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Lygodium ambiguum?''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Various Locations\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMicroparts of leafs and assigned Pollen.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Lygodiaceae]].\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n[[Andreaea]]?<ref name=Plant1></ref>\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*''Andreaea sp.?''\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n*Various Locations\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nMicroparts of leafs and assigned Pollen.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\nAffinities with the [[Andreaeaceae]]. Maybe a mistaken generical Lycophyta Pollen.\n|style=\"background:#D1FFCF;\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n==Invertebrata==\n====Cephalopoda====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Eleganticeras]]<ref>Lehmann, U. (1967). Ammoniten mit Kieferapparat und Radula aus Lias-Geschieben. Pal\u00e4ontologische Zeitschrift, 41(1-2), 38-45.</ref><ref>Howarth, M. K., & Rawson, P. F. (1965).The Liassic succession in a clay pit at Kirton in Lindsey, north Lincolnshire. Geological Magazine, 102(3), 261-266.</ref><ref>van de Schootbrugge, B., McArthur, J. M., Bailey, T. R., Rosenthal, Y., Wright, J. D., & Miller, K. G. (2005). Toarcian oceanic anoxic event: An assessment of global causes using belemnite C isotope records. Paleoceanography, 20(3).</ref>\n|\n*''Eleganticeras elegantulum''\n|\n* Green Series\n* Boulder from Ahrensburg\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[Hildoceratidae]] [[Ammonite]].\n|\n[[File:Harpoceras elegans.jpg|thumb|center|225px|''[[Eleganticeras]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Tiltoniceras]]<ref>ZESSIN, W. (2010). Der Dobbertiner Jura (Lias \u03b5, Mecklenburg) und seine Bedeutung f\u00fcr die Pal\u00e4oentomologie. Virgo, Mitteilungsblatt des Entomologischen Vereins Mecklenburg, 13(1), 4-9.</ref><ref>Lehmann, U. (1966). Dimorphismus bei Ammoniten der Ahrensburger Lias-Geschiebe. Pal\u00e4ontologische Zeitschrift, 40(1-2), 26-55.</ref>\n|\n*''Tiltoniceras antiquum''\n*''Tiltoniceras sp.''\n|\n* Green Series\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[Hildoceratidae]] [[Ammonite]].\n|\n[[File:Tiltoniceras antiquum - Naturhistorisches Museum, Braunschweig, Germany - DSC05134.JPG|thumb|center|225px|''[[Tiltoniceras]]'']]\n|-\n|\n[[Lobolytoceras]]<ref>Hoffmann, R., Schultz, J. A., Schellhorn, R., Rybacki, E., Keupp, H., Lemanis, R., & Zachow, S. (2014). Non-invasive imaging methods applied to neo-and paleo-ontological cephalopod research.</ref><ref>L\u00fcrnG, G. (1995). Geschiebez\u00e4hlungen-eine terminologische Richtigstellung. Geschiebekunde aktuell, 11(4), 109-112.</ref>\n|\n*''Lobolytoceras siemensi''\n|\n* Green Series\n|\nMultiple Specimens.\n|\nA [[Lytoceratidae]] [[Ammonite]].\n|\n[[File:Lobolytoceras siemensi low.jpg|thumb|center|225px|''[[Lobolytoceras]]'']]\n|-\n|}\n\n====Arachnida====\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Seppo koponeni]]<ref>Selden, Paul A.; Dunlop, Jason A. (2014). \"The first fossil spider (Araneae: Palpimanoidea) from the Lower Jurassic (Grimmen, Germany)\". Zootaxa. 3894 (1): 161\u2013168. doi:10.11646/zootaxa.3894.1.13.</ref>\n|\n*''Seppo koponeni'' \n|\n* Green Series\n|\nSingle Incomplete Specimen.\n|\nA possible member of the superfamily [[Palpimanoidea]]. It is the first confirmed spider from the lower jurassic, and a rare find, probably washed to the sea due to a hard vind related to hurricane action, present due to the measured moonsonal conditions of the formation, as on the rest of the Lower-Middle Toarcian strata. Probably a ground dewelling predator that hunted the abundant insect fauna present on the layers.\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n====Insecta====\nInsects are a common terrestrial animals that where proabaly drifted to the sea due to Moonsonal conditions present on the Ciechocinek Formation.<ref>Ansorge, J. (2003). Insects from the lower Toarcian of middle Europe and England. Acta zoologica cracoviensia, 46(SUPPL.), 291-310.</ref>\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n[[Zalmonites]]\n|\n*''Zalmonites geinitzi''\n|\n* Green Series\n|\nSeveral Specimens\n|\nA [[Grasshopper]].\n|\n|-\n|\n[[Panorpidium]]<ref>W. Zessin. 1983. Revision der mesozoischen Familie Locustopsidae unter Ber\u00fccksichtigung neuer Funde (Orthopteroida, Caelifera). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 30:173-237</ref><ref>W. Zessin. 1987. Variabilit\u00e4t, Merkmalswandel und Phylogenie der Elcanidae im Jungpal\u00e4ozoikum und Mesozoikum und die Phylogenie der Ensifera. Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 34(1-3):1-76</ref>\n|\n*''Panorpidium geinitzi'' \n*''Panorpidium magna'' \n*''Panorpidium minima'' \n*''Panorpidium media'' \n*''Panorpidium reticulata''<ref>A. Handlirsch. 1920. Palaeontologie. In C. Schr\u00f6der (ed.), Handbuch der Entomologie 3:117-208</ref>\n