2018-09-13}}</ref><br/>{{color|#0c0|high}} \u00b7 [[List of regions of North Macedonia by Human Development Index|1st of 8]]\n| website                         = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                       = \n| coordinates                     = \n| area_urban_footnotes            = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_rural_footnotes            = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n| area_metro_footnotes            = <!-- <ref> </ref> -->\n}}\n\nThe '''Skopje Statistical Region''' ({{lang-mk|\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d}}, {{lang-sq|Shkup}}) is one of eight [[Statistical regions of North Macedonia]]. Skopje, located in the north of the country, borders [[Kosovo]] to the north. Internally, it borders the [[Vardar Statistical Region|Vardar]], [[Polog Statistical Region|Polog]], [[Northeastern Statistical Region|Northeastern]], [[Eastern Statistical Region|Eastern]], and [[Southwestern Statistical Region|Southwestern]] statistical regions.\n\n==Municipalities==\n[[File:Map of the municipalities of Skopje Statistical Region en.svg|300px|right|thumb|The municipalities of the region]]\nThe region consists of the [[Skopje|City of Skopje]] and the following municipalities:\n*[[Ara\u010dinovo Municipality|Ara\u010dinovo]]\n*[[\u010cu\u010der-Sandevo Municipality|\u010cu\u010der-Sandevo]]\n*[[Ilinden Municipality|Ilinden]]\n*[[Petrovec Municipality|Petrovec]]\n*[[Sopi\u0161te Municipality|Sopi\u0161te]]\n*[[Studeni\u010dani Municipality|Studeni\u010dani]]\n*[[Zelenikovo Municipality|Zelenikovo]]\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Ethnic groups in Skopje Region of North Macedonia en.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of the majority ethnic groups in the region]]\n\n===Population===\nThe current population of the Skopje Statistical Region is 578,144 citizens, according to the last population census in 2002, accounting for 28.6% of the total national population. The region is the largest by population in North Macedonia.\n\n===Ethnicities===\n{| border=1 cellpadding=4 cellspacing=0 class=\"toccolours\" style=\"align: left; margin: 0.5em 0 0 0; border-style: solid; border: 1px solid #7f7f7f; border-right-width: 2px; border-bottom-width: 2px; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- \n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" |\n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" align=\"center\" | <small>Number</small>\n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" align=\"center\" | <small>%</small> \n|- \n| style=\"background:#c1c1c1;\" | '''TOTAL'''\n| style=\"background:#c1c1c1;\" | '''578,144'''\n| style=\"background:#c1c1c1;\" | 100 \n|- \n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]]\n| 367,413\n| 63.6\n|- \n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Albanians]]\n| 133,893\n| 23.2\n|- \n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Romani people|Roma]]\n| 23,903\n| 4.1\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Serbs]]\n| 18,051\n| 3.1\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Turkish people|Turks]]\n| 12,123\n| 2.1\n|-\n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | [[Bosniaks]]\n| 10,880\n| 1.9\n|- \n| style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\" | others \n| 11,881\n| 2.1 \n|}\n\n<br/>\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Regions of Macedonia}}\n{{Skopje}}\n\n{{coord|42.0000|N|21.4333|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Statistical regions of North Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Skopje]]\n[[Category:Ara\u010dinovo Municipality]]\n[[Category:\u010cu\u010der-Sandevo Municipality]]\n[[Category:Ilinden Municipality]]\n[[Category:Petrovec Municipality]]\n[[Category:Sopi\u0161te Municipality]]\n[[Category:Studeni\u010dani Municipality]]\n[[Category:Zelenikovo Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Redzovic", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skopje_Statistical_Region"}
{"title_page": "Dashuhua", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese Festival of Lights tradition in Nuanquan Town}}\n{{further|Chinese paper cutting}}\n{{Infobox performing art\n| name       = Da Shuhua\n| image      = Da Shuhua.jpg\n| caption    = Blacksmiths threw molten iron to create sparks on February 19th, 2019\n| medium     = Visual\n| types      = Performing art(visual art)\n| ancestor   = Local blacksmiths in Nuanquan\n| descendant = \n| culture    = China\n| era        = Fifteenth century\n}}\n'''Da Shuhua''' or '''Dashuhua''' ({{zh|s=\u6253\u6811\u82b1|p=d\u01cesh\u00f9hu\u0101}}) is a Chinese [[Lantern Festival|Festival of Lights]] tradition in Nuanquan Town,<ref>{{Cite news|title=FEB. 28 IRON TRIBE PERFORMANCE POUR|last=|first=|date=15 Feb 2019|work=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|id = {{ProQuest|2180091610}}}}</ref> with a history of more than five hundred years. It is shown by throwing molten iron against cold bricks to create showers of sparks which have a similar shape of leafy [[Canopy (biology)|tree canopy]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|title=Watch: Dazzling Poor Man's Fireworks in a Chinese Steel City|last=|first=|date=23 Feb 2015|work=Dow Jones Institutional News|id = {{ProQuest|2068775422}}}}</ref> Da Shuhua has been classified as one of [[China]]'s significant examples of [[intangible cultural heritage]] by [[UNESCO]] (United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization ),<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?&id=GALE%7CA527076374&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|title=Some places to celebrate Lunar New Year|last=|first=|date=11 Feb 2018|work=Iran Daily (Tehran Iran)|access-date=}}</ref> and the provincial intangible cultural heritage in [[Hebei]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201809/17/WS5b9f6931a31033b4f46567c3.html|title='Dashuhua' \u2013 China's unique molten iron throwing tradition|last=|first=|date=17 Sep 2018|website=China Daily|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It marks the start of the [[Dragon Boat Festival]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|title=Sparkling welcome Molten iron is [...]|last=|first=|date=31 May 2017|work=The Times|id = {{ProQuest|1904847481}}}}</ref> and also used to celebrate the [[Lunar New Year|Lunar New Year in China]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|title=China: Sparks fly for Lunar New Year in ancient light show|last=|first=|date=21 Feb 2019|work=Asia News Monitor|id = {{ProQuest|2183727002}}}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Etymology===\n\u201cDa Shuhua\u201d is the English term for the art form, literally meaning \"beating tree flowers\u201d. The blacksmiths in Nuanquan named the art as Da Shuhua because the outcome of it has a shape of the leafy [[Canopy (biology)|tree canopy]].<ref name=\":2\" /> When the blacksmiths throw the molten iron against the wall, the flying sparks will present a look of tree flower.\n\n===Origins===\nDa Shuhua is found in Nuanquan Township, [[Yu County, Hebei|Yuxian County]], located Northwest of [[Beijing]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Chan|first=Wilfred|date=2018|title=Between the Lines|journal=Art AisaPacific Almanac|volume=13|pages=221\u2013225|id={{ProQuest|2113421955}}}}</ref> which was built in the [[Ming dynasty]] (1368-1644) as a presidio for Beijing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?p=ITOF&u=usyd&id=GALE%7CA574655540&v=2.1&it=r|title=Across China: Throwing molten iron -- a dangerous and dazzling firework art|last=|first=|date=19 Feb 2019|work=Xinhua News Agency|access-date=}}</ref> Nuanquan Town, literally meaning Warm Spring Town, and the name \u201cNuanquan\u201d came from the fact that there was a hot spring. It is an ancient town surrounded by mountains and has a reputation of \u201cthe First Ancient Town of Jiangxi\uff08western area of Beijing\uff09\u201d. People have lived in Nuanquan since the [[Warring States period|Warring States Period]](475BC-221BC). There are 20,000 people currently live in Nuanquan, and the historical features and cultural heritages there are well-protected in the process of modernization. The home of Da Shuhua also known as \u201cHometown of Paper Cutting\u201d. Yuxian-style paper cuts combined [[Papercutting|paper cutting]] with theatric features and adopts woodblock watermark and Yangliuqing painting technology. The colorful and creative paper cuts are designed for decorating windows, which can enhance the festival atmosphere during the festival season. The wide variety of theatre stages in Yuxian illustrates that local folks love about [[Chinese Theatre|Chinese theatre]] as well, and the theatres were built with delicate porcelain tiles and painted with exquisite fresco.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Yue|date=2012|title=Historic County of Yuxian|journal=China & the World Cultural Exchange|volume=|pages=1|id={{ProQuest|1238006147}}}}</ref>\n\nIn ancient times, the Lunar New Year is the busiest time of the year in Nuanquan Town.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Ping|date=2006|title=Nuanquan: Basking in Celebrity|url=http://www.cnki.com.cn/Article/CJFDTotal-ZFLW200604025.htm|journal=China Academic Journal Electronic Publishing House|volume=|pages=73|via=}}</ref> The rich used expensive [[fireworks]] to celebrate the festival with the sounds and sparks of explosions, while the poor could not afford it<sup>8</sup>. The ironmaking industry in Nuanquan was flourished grounded on the weapon manufacturing, and the blacksmiths there inspired by the flakes of heated iron when they tried to find a cheap way to celebrate the festival. They found that the sparks created by the collision between heated iron with the cold wall have a similar scene of fireworks. Later, the poor collected waste iron and gave to local blacksmiths to perform Da Shuhua as a form of reveling and attracted more and more people who could not afford to buy real fireworks came to watch. The three-day show usually performs in the 15th of the first [[lunar month]], and it develops the tradition that during the Lunar New year, the rich watches fireworks and the poor watches Da Shuhua. At the very beginning, Da Shuhua was performed on a cold wall in Nuanquan. As the population of the audience getting bigger and bigger, local people built a square which is used explicitly for performing Da Shuhua and named it \u201cTree Flower Square\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />  The future of the art is uncertain because the four remaining artists are all over fifty years old.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Tourism ===\nThe fortress of Xigubao(Chinese: \u897f\u53e4\u5821) has been listed among the national nonmaterial cultural heritage in 2001 by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council of China]]. Xigubao is located in Nuanquan town, Yuxian county. Both small and large temples in the fortress were built in the [[Ming dynasty]] and decorated with ancient fresco.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/hebei/travel/2010-09/29/content_12292827.htm|title=Country escapes|last=|first=|date=29 Sep 2010|work=Global Times|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:Yuxian, Zhangjiakou, Hebei, China - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|Da Shuhua arose in Yuxian County in 500 years ago.]]\n\n== Performance process ==\nThe traditional performing process of Da Shuhua did not change much for more than 500 years. It takes four folk artists to perform and usually takes place in the Tree Flower Square of Nuanquan township. There will be one leader blacksmith, and the other three will assist the leader with managing his iron [[furnace]] during the performance. The artists need to collect more than 500 kilograms waste iron and melt them for at least half an hour in a furnace with high heat before the show. The wooden spoon is the primary tool for Da Shuhua, and the production process of it is cumbersome. The raw material of the spoon is [[willow]] root. The root needs to be soaked in water for a few days at first, and then blacksmiths will use small fire to dry it to make it anti-burning. The four blacksmiths have to wear [[straw hat]]s and thick [[sheepskin coat]]s to protect themselves from the splashing molten iron during performance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Before Dashuhua starts, performances such as dragon lantern dance, [[lion dance]] and land boat dance will be performed by folk artists of Nuanquan first. According to the record, during the show, the molten metal will be heated up to {{cvt|1600|\u00b0C}}.<ref name=\":1\" />  The art of Da Shuhua requires skills, power, and courage. When the leader artist scoops up the heavy iron from the furnace with the wooden spoon, the spoon cannot go very deep. Otherwise, the temperature difference between the cold spoon and heated iron will cause an explosion. Then the leader blacksmith throws the spoonful of iron on the cold wall through the burst of strength on his arms and the blast of liquid iron from the wall gives the audience showers of sparks. At the end of the show, the artists will perform a deep kowtow in front of the furnace and pray for happiness and good luck. The danger of Da Shuhua can be reflected from the wounds on those folk artists. The leader blacksmith of the performance team in recent years is Wang De (artist), whose father and grandfather were both blacksmiths. Wang said he suffered a burn on his leg years ago, and it took him two months to recover.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scientific principle ===\nThe [[melting point]] of [[iron]] is {{cvt|1538|\u00b0C}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Okamato|first=H.|date=Aug 1990|title=The Fe-Te (Iron-Tellurium) system|journal=Bulletin of Alloy Phase Diagrams|volume=11|issue=4|pages=371\u2013376|doi=10.1007/BF02843316}}</ref> When blacksmiths heat the iron up to {{cvt|1600|\u00b0C}} Celsius, the solid iron will melt and turn into liquid iron. The splash of heated liquid iron is an [[energy transformation]] process. The [[potential energy]] of the surface of liquid iron transforms to [[kinetic energy]] when the blacksmith throws out the iron from the furnace. The explosion of molten iron is essentially an [[oxidation reaction]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kress|first=V.C|date=1988|title=Stoichiometry of the iron oxidation reaction in silicate melts.|url=http://www.minsocam.org/ammin/AM73/AM73_1267.pdf|journal=American Mineralogist|volume=73|pages=1267\u20131274|via=}}</ref>  When the blacksmith flings the molten iron against the wall, the carbon impurity in the iron will react with oxygen to produce [[carbon dioxide]] and the impact between the carbon in the iron and the cold wall will react and produce sparks. With the same performance process, the higher the carbon amount of the iron, the more sparks can be formed.\n\n==Television drama==\nThe first TV series that involved Da Shuhua is called \u201c[[Story of Yanxi Palace]].\" \"Story of Yanxi Palace\u201d is a popular TV series in the summer of 2018. On average, it was being streamed 300 million times a day. The series is talking about harem life during the reign of [[Qianlong Emperor|Emperor Qianlong]] (1711\u201399) in the [[Qing dynasty|Qing Dynasty]] (1644-1911).<ref>{{Cite news|title=iQIYI's Summer Smash Hit Drama \"Story of Yanxi Palace\" Comes to a Close, Being Streamed Over 15 Billion Times: Costume drama set in the Forbidden City concludes blinding run as the most talked about show this summer, breaking multiple viewership records|last=|first=|date=31 Aug 2018|work=PR Newswire|id={{ProQuest|2097431620}}}}</ref> In this series, Da Shuhua is called \u201cWan Zi Qian Hong\u201d, a Chinese four-character phrase which means \"colors of flame\" and the noble consort of Qianlong invites some folk blacksmiths to perform it for Qianlong's mother to celebrate her birthday.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201808/30/WS5b8732e3a310add14f38887c_1.html|title=Back in the limelight|last=Fang|first=Aiqing|date=30 Aug 2018|website=China Daily|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Along with the influence of \u201cStory of Yanxi Palace\u201d, the audience awareness of Da Shuhua was improved.\n\n==Book==\nJapanese photographer [[Rinko Kawauchi]]'s book: ''Halo'', is a collection of photos of Da Shuhua. It was awarded as one of the notable photo books of 2007,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Walker|first=David|date=2017|title=NOTABLE PHOTO BOOKS of 2017|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA515125194&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|journal=Photo District News|volume=37|issue=12|pages=42(7)|via=}}</ref> and these photos show clouds of sparks which created by the collision between iron and wall. Kawauchi said in the last pages of ''Halo'': \u201cWe still find ourselves yearning to witness beauty. Our ceaseless desire to do so is like a prayer.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Poem ==\n[[File:A Painting of Li Bai with his poetry.jpg|thumb|Li Bai, a Chinese poet in Tang Dynasty.]]\nThe \u201csongs of Qiupu\u201d (Chinese: \u79cb\u6d66\u6b4c\u5341\u4e03\u9996) is the earliest record of Da Shuhua. It is a collection of seventeen poems which was written by [[Li Bai]](AD701-762), a poet in [[Tang dynasty|Tang Dynasty]] (AD618-907).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liscomb|first=Kathlyn Maurean|date=Sep 1999|title=Li Bai, a hero among poets, in the visual, dramatic, and literary arts of China|journal=The Art Bulletin|volume=81|issue=3|pages=354\u2013389|doi=10.2307/3051348|jstor=3051348|id={{ProQuest|222965459}}}}</ref> When Li wrote this poem he was already fifty years old and visiting Qiupu (\u79cb\u6d66). Qiupu is a place in today's [[Anhui|Anhui province]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cityguide/2008-08/12/content_6927393.htm|title=Song of Qiupu|last=|first=|date=12 Aug 2008|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref> During Tang Dynasty, the art that Li Bai recorded is the ancient form of Da Shuhua, which has the similar performance process and outcome with Da Shuhua. The verse which describes the view of the ancient show is in the fourteenth poem of \u201csongs of Qiupu\u201d, \u201c\u7089\u706b\u7167\u5929\u5730\uff0c\u7ea2\u661f\u4e71\u7d2b\u70df\u3002\u201d.  It translated to \u201cTheir furnace fire illumes both earth and sky, Red parks spiking its purple smoke awry.\u201d by Andrew Wong,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinesepoemsinenglish.blogspot.com/2011/08/li-bai-song-of-qiupu-xiv-first-line.html|title=Song of Qiupu 14 of 17 (1--Their furnace fire illumes both earth and sky)|last=Wong|first=Andrew W.F.|date=14 Aug 2011|website=Classical Chinese Poems in English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which states showers of sparks of the art created by the ancient blacksmiths. The difference of the outcomes between Da Shuhua and the predecessor of it is that there was purple smoke formed during performance in the Tang Dynasty. The \"songs of Qiupu\" expresses the emotions of Li Bai with the image.\n\n== Festivals ==\n\n=== The Lantern Festival ===\n[[File:Lantern Festival (Chinese characters).svg|left|thumb|Words of \"Lantern festival\" in Chinese characters]]\nThe [[Lantern Festival]](Chinese: \u5143\u5bb5\u8282) is a time for everyone to be with their families. The three-day show, Da Shuhua performs around the [[Lunar New Year]] to celebrate the Lantern Festival in Nuanquan. The Lantern Festival is an ancient festival and usually celebrated on the fifteenth day of the first lunar month. Although it occurs two weeks after the [[Spring Festival - China|Spring Festival]], it is a popular time of the year as it marks the end of the traditional Chinese New Year celebration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alina|date=Jan-Mar 2017|title=The Lantern Festival|url=|journal=Skipping Stones|volume=|pages=15|via=}}</ref> During the Lantern Festival, local residents gather at the Tree Flower square, in the center of Nuanquan town, for Da Shuhua. On the Lantern Festival, the celebrations of Nuanquan Town start in the morning of the day and continue late into the midnight.<ref name=\":5\" /> Da Shuhua is a way of expressing good wishes that local people prayed for happiness, health and prosperity in the new year. In other places of China, people hung red lanterns outside their windows, eat [[Tangyuan (food)|yuanxiao]](Chinese\uff1a\u5143\u5bb5)and shoot off [[firecracker]]s to celebrate the Lantern Festival.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/sunday/2013-02/24/content_16251429.htm|title=Bright sparks|last=|first=|date=24 Feb 2013|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== The Dragon Boat Festival ===\nDa Shuhua marks the start of the [[Dragon Boat Festival]] (Chinese:\u7aef\u5348\u8282).<ref name=\":4\" /> The Dragon Boat Festival occurs on the fifth day of May of the lunar year, which is a [[Public holidays in China|public holiday in China]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Muxue\"Snow\"|date=Apr-Jun 2018|title=Dragon Boat Festival|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA535236050&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|journal=Skipping Stones|volume=|pages=24|via=}}</ref> The performers of Da Shuhua will start working on the Dragon Boat Festival and every weekend of the second half of the year until the end of the Lantern Festival which marks the end of the Spring Festival. Eating [[zongzi]] (sticky rice dumpling) and racing [[dragon boat]]s are also the traditional activities that people used to celebrate the festival.\n\n== Artists ==\n\n=== Wang De ===\nWang De, who is the lead performer of Da Shuhua in China. Wang was born in Nuanquan, in nineteen sixty-four. As one of the inheritors of Da Shuhua, Wang learned it from his father when he was young. Wang earns 300 [[Yuan (currency)|yuan]] for each show and works on the weekend during the second half of the year and the Spring Festival. The Lantern Festival is the busiest time of the year for Wang. For the rest of the time, Wang grows [[corn]]. Wang has two sons and he passes his skills to his younger son, who was born in nineteen ninety-seven.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/21/WS5c6de8e1a3106c65c34ea74f_2.html|title=Molten iron fireworks shows add sparkle to town in Hebei|last=|first=|date=21 Feb 2019|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Sui Jianguo ===\nSui is a 14th generation blacksmith in Nuanquan. He has been performing the art for 25 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/chinese-year-fireworks-dangerous-witness/story?id=36792195|title=Chinese New Year Fireworks So Dangerous That Only a Few Get to Witness|last=Yiu|first=Karson|date=8 Feb 2016|work=ABC News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Yu Zhangliang ===\nYu is the artist from Nuanquan who took part in the \u201cStory of Yanxi Palace\u201d and performed Da Shuhua in the series.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chinese paper cutting]]\n*[[Story of Yanxi Palace]]\n*[[Yu County, Hebei|Yuxian County]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Chinese New Year|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Festivals in China]]\n[[Category:Lantern Festival]]\n[[Category:Culture in Hebei]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese Festival of Lights tradition in Nuanquan Town}}\n{{further|Chinese paper cutting}}\n{{Infobox performing art\n| name       = Da Shuhua\n| image      = Da Shuhua.jpg\n| caption    = Blacksmiths threw molten iron to create sparks on February 19th, 2019\n| medium     = Visual\n| types      = Performing art(visual art)\n| ancestor   = Local blacksmiths in Nuanquan\n| descendant = \n| culture    = China\n| era        = Fifteenth century\n}}\n'''Da Shuhua''' or '''Dashuhua''' ({{zh|s=\u6253\u6811\u82b1|p=d\u01cesh\u00f9hu\u0101}}) is a Chinese [[Lantern Festival|Festival of Lights]] tradition in Nuanquan Town,<ref>{{Cite news|title=FEB. 28 IRON TRIBE PERFORMANCE POUR|last=|first=|date=15 Feb 2019|work=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|id = {{ProQuest|2180091610}}}}</ref> with a history of more than five hundred years. It is shown by throwing molten iron against cold bricks to create showers of sparks which have a similar shape of leafy [[Canopy (biology)|tree canopy]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|title=Watch: Dazzling Poor Man's Fireworks in a Chinese Steel City|last=|first=|date=23 Feb 2015|work=Dow Jones Institutional News|id = {{ProQuest|2068775422}}}}</ref> Da Shuhua has been classified as one of [[China]]'s significant examples of [[intangible cultural heritage]] by [[UNESCO]] (United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization ),<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?&id=GALE%7CA527076374&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|title=Some places to celebrate Lunar New Year|last=|first=|date=11 Feb 2018|work=Iran Daily (Tehran Iran)|access-date=}}</ref> and the provincial intangible cultural heritage in [[Hebei]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://global.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201809/17/WS5b9f6931a31033b4f46567c3.html|title='Dashuhua' \u2013 China's unique molten iron throwing tradition|last=|first=|date=17 Sep 2018|website=China Daily|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It marks the start of the [[Dragon Boat Festival]]<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|title=Sparkling welcome Molten iron is [...]|last=|first=|date=31 May 2017|work=The Times|id = {{ProQuest|1904847481}}}}</ref> and also used to celebrate the [[Lunar New Year|Lunar New Year in China]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|title=China: Sparks fly for Lunar New Year in ancient light show|last=|first=|date=21 Feb 2019|work=Asia News Monitor|id = {{ProQuest|2183727002}}}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Etymology===\n\u201cDa Shuhua\u201d is the English term for the art form, literally meaning \"beating tree flowers\u201d. The blacksmiths in Nuanquan named the art as Da Shuhua because the outcome of it has a shape of the leafy [[Canopy (biology)|tree canopy]].<ref name=\":2\" /> When the blacksmiths throw the molten iron against the wall, the flying sparks will present a look of tree flower.\n\n===Origins===\nDa Shuhua is found in Nuanquan Township, [[Yu County, Hebei|Yuxian County]], located Northwest of [[Beijing]],<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Chan|first=Wilfred|date=2018|title=Between the Lines|journal=Art AisaPacific Almanac|volume=13|pages=221\u2013225|id={{ProQuest|2113421955}}}}</ref> which was built in the [[Ming dynasty]] (1368-1644) as a presidio for Beijing.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?p=ITOF&u=usyd&id=GALE%7CA574655540&v=2.1&it=r|title=Across China: Throwing molten iron -- a dangerous and dazzling firework art|last=|first=|date=19 Feb 2019|work=Xinhua News Agency|access-date=}}</ref> Nuanquan Town, literally meaning Warm Spring Town, and the name \u201cNuanquan\u201d came from the fact that there was a hot spring. It is an ancient town surrounded by mountains and has a reputation of \u201cthe First Ancient Town of Jiangxi\uff08western area of Beijing\uff09\u201d. People have lived in Nuanquan since the [[Warring States period|Warring States Period]](475BC-221BC). There are 20,000 people currently live in Nuanquan, and the historical features and cultural heritages there are well-protected in the process of modernization. The home of Da Shuhua also known as \u201cHometown of Paper Cutting\u201d. Yuxian-style paper cuts combined [[Papercutting|paper cutting]] with theatric features and adopts woodblock watermark and Yangliuqing painting technology. The colorful and creative paper cuts are designed for decorating windows, which can enhance the festival atmosphere during the festival season. The wide variety of theatre stages in Yuxian illustrates that local folks love about [[Chinese Theatre|Chinese theatre]] as well, and the theatres were built with delicate porcelain tiles and painted with exquisite fresco.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Yue|date=2012|title=Historic County of Yuxian|journal=China & the World Cultural Exchange|volume=|pages=1|id={{ProQuest|1238006147}}}}</ref>\n\nIn ancient times, the Lunar New Year is the busiest time of the year in Nuanquan Town.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=Ping|date=2006|title=Nuanquan: Basking in Celebrity|url=http://www.cnki.com.cn/Article/CJFDTotal-ZFLW200604025.htm|journal=China Academic Journal Electronic Publishing House|volume=|pages=73|via=}}</ref> The rich used expensive [[fireworks]] to celebrate the festival with the sounds and sparks of explosions, while the poor could not afford it<sup>8</sup>. The ironmaking industry in Nuanquan was flourished grounded on the weapon manufacturing, and the blacksmiths there inspired by the flakes of heated iron when they tried to find a cheap way to celebrate the festival. They found that the sparks created by the collision between heated iron with the cold wall have a similar scene of fireworks. Later, the poor collected waste iron and gave to local blacksmiths to perform Da Shuhua as a form of reveling and attracted more and more people who could not afford to buy real fireworks came to watch. The three-day show usually performs in the 15th of the first [[lunar month]], and it develops the tradition that during the Lunar New year, the rich watches fireworks and the poor watches Da Shuhua. At the very beginning, Da Shuhua was performed on a cold wall in Nuanquan. As the population of the audience getting bigger and bigger, local people built a square which is used explicitly for performing Da Shuhua and named it \u201cTree Flower Square\u201d.<ref name=\":0\" />  The future of the art is uncertain because the four remaining artists are all over fifty years old.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Tourism ===\nThe fortress of Xigubao(Chinese: \u897f\u53e4\u5821) has been listed among the national nonmaterial cultural heritage in 2001 by the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council of China]]. Xigubao is located in Nuanquan town, Yuxian county. Both small and large temples in the fortress were built in the [[Ming dynasty]] and decorated with ancient fresco.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/m/hebei/travel/2010-09/29/content_12292827.htm|title=Country escapes|last=|first=|date=29 Sep 2010|work=Global Times|access-date=}}</ref>[[File:Yuxian, Zhangjiakou, Hebei, China - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|Da Shuhua arose in Yuxian County in 500 years ago.]]\n\n== Performance process ==\nThe traditional performing process of Da Shuhua did not change much for more than 500 years. It takes four folk artists to perform and usually takes place in the Tree Flower Square of Nuanquan township. There will be one leader blacksmith, and the other three will assist the leader with managing his iron [[furnace]] during the performance. The artists need to collect more than 500 kilograms waste iron and melt them for at least half an hour in a furnace with high heat before the show. The wooden spoon is the primary tool for Da Shuhua, and the production process of it is cumbersome. The raw material of the spoon is [[willow]] root. The root needs to be soaked in water for a few days at first, and then blacksmiths will use small fire to dry it to make it anti-burning. The four blacksmiths have to wear [[straw hat]]s and thick [[sheepskin coat]]s to protect themselves from the splashing molten iron during performance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Before Dashuhua starts, performances such as dragon lantern dance, [[lion dance]] and land boat dance will be performed by folk artists of Nuanquan first. According to the record, during the show, the molten metal will be heated up to {{cvt|1600|\u00b0C}}.<ref name=\":1\" />  The art of Da Shuhua requires skills, power, and courage. When the leader artist scoops up the heavy iron from the furnace with the wooden spoon, the spoon cannot go very deep. Otherwise, the temperature difference between the cold spoon and heated iron will cause an explosion. Then the leader blacksmith throws the spoonful of iron on the cold wall through the burst of strength on his arms and the blast of liquid iron from the wall gives the audience showers of sparks. At the end of the show, the artists will perform a deep kowtow in front of the furnace and pray for happiness and good luck. The danger of Da Shuhua can be reflected from the wounds on those folk artists. The leader blacksmith of the performance team in recent years is Wang De (artist), whose father and grandfather were both blacksmiths. Wang said he suffered a burn on his leg years ago, and it took him two months to recover.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Scientific principle ===\nThe [[melting point]] of [[iron]] is {{cvt|1538|\u00b0C}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Okamato|first=H.|date=Aug 1990|title=The Fe-Te (Iron-Tellurium) system|journal=Bulletin of Alloy Phase Diagrams|volume=11|issue=4|pages=371\u2013376|doi=10.1007/BF02843316}}</ref> When blacksmiths heat the iron up to {{cvt|1600|\u00b0C}} Celsius, the solid iron will melt and turn into liquid iron. The splash of heated liquid iron is an [[energy transformation]] process. The [[potential energy]] of the surface of liquid iron transforms to [[kinetic energy]] when the blacksmith throws out the iron from the furnace. The explosion of molten iron is essentially an [[oxidation reaction]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kress|first=V.C|date=1988|title=Stoichiometry of the iron oxidation reaction in silicate melts.|url=http://www.minsocam.org/ammin/AM73/AM73_1267.pdf|journal=American Mineralogist|volume=73|pages=1267\u20131274|via=}}</ref>  When the blacksmith flings the molten iron against the wall, the carbon impurity in the iron will react with oxygen to produce [[carbon dioxide]] and the impact between the carbon in the iron and the cold wall will react and produce sparks. With the same performance process, the higher the carbon amount of the iron, the more sparks can be formed.\n\n==Television drama==\nThe first TV series that involved Da Shuhua is called \u201c[[Story of Yanxi Palace]].\" \"Story of Yanxi Palace\u201d is a popular TV series in the summer of 2018. On average, it was being streamed 300 million times a day. The series is talking about harem life during the reign of [[Qianlong Emperor|Emperor Qianlong]] (1711\u201399) in the [[Qing dynasty|Qing Dynasty]] (1644-1911).<ref>{{Cite news|title=iQIYI's Summer Smash Hit Drama \"Story of Yanxi Palace\" Comes to a Close, Being Streamed Over 15 Billion Times: Costume drama set in the Forbidden City concludes blinding run as the most talked about show this summer, breaking multiple viewership records|last=|first=|date=31 Aug 2018|work=PR Newswire|id={{ProQuest|2097431620}}}}</ref> In this series, Da Shuhua is called \u201cWan Zi Qian Hong\u201d, a Chinese four-character phrase which means \"colors of flame\" and the noble consort of Qianlong invites some folk blacksmiths to perform it for Qianlong's mother to celebrate her birthday.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201808/30/WS5b8732e3a310add14f38887c_1.html|title=Back in the limelight|last=Fang|first=Aiqing|date=30 Aug 2018|website=China Daily|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Along with the influence of \u201cStory of Yanxi Palace\u201d, the audience awareness of Da Shuhua was improved.\n\n==Book==\nJapanese photographer [[Rinko Kawauchi]]'s book: ''Halo'', is a collection of photos of Da Shuhua. It was awarded as one of the notable photo books of 2007,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Walker|first=David|date=2017|title=NOTABLE PHOTO BOOKS of 2017|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA515125194&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|journal=Photo District News|volume=37|issue=12|pages=42(7)|via=}}</ref> and these photos show clouds of sparks which created by the collision between iron and wall. Kawauchi said in the last pages of ''Halo'': \u201cWe still find ourselves yearning to witness beauty. Our ceaseless desire to do so is like a prayer.\u201d<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Poem ==\n[[File:A Painting of Li Bai with his poetry.jpg|thumb|Li Bai, a Chinese poet in Tang Dynasty.]]\nThe \u201csongs of Qiupu\u201d (Chinese: \u79cb\u6d66\u6b4c\u5341\u4e03\u9996) is the earliest record of Da Shuhua. It is a collection of seventeen poems which was written by [[Li Bai]](AD701-762), a poet in [[Tang dynasty|Tang Dynasty]] (AD618-907).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liscomb|first=Kathlyn Maurean|date=Sep 1999|title=Li Bai, a hero among poets, in the visual, dramatic, and literary arts of China|journal=The Art Bulletin|volume=81|issue=3|pages=354\u2013389|doi=10.2307/3051348|jstor=3051348|id={{ProQuest|222965459}}}}</ref> When Li wrote this poem he was already fifty years old and visiting Qiupu (\u79cb\u6d66). Qiupu is a place in today's [[Anhui|Anhui province]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cityguide/2008-08/12/content_6927393.htm|title=Song of Qiupu|last=|first=|date=12 Aug 2008|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref> During Tang Dynasty, the art that Li Bai recorded is the ancient form of Da Shuhua, which has the similar performance process and outcome with Da Shuhua. The verse which describes the view of the ancient show is in the fourteenth poem of \u201csongs of Qiupu\u201d, \u201c\u7089\u706b\u7167\u5929\u5730\uff0c\u7ea2\u661f\u4e71\u7d2b\u70df\u3002\u201d.  It translated to \u201cTheir furnace fire illumes both earth and sky, Red parks spiking its purple smoke awry.\u201d by Andrew Wong,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chinesepoemsinenglish.blogspot.com/2011/08/li-bai-song-of-qiupu-xiv-first-line.html|title=Song of Qiupu 14 of 17 (1--Their furnace fire illumes both earth and sky)|last=Wong|first=Andrew W.F.|date=14 Aug 2011|website=Classical Chinese Poems in English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> which states showers of sparks of the art created by the ancient blacksmiths. The difference of the outcomes between Da Shuhua and the predecessor of it is that there was purple smoke formed during performance in the Tang Dynasty. The \"songs of Qiupu\" expresses the emotions of Li Bai with the image.\n\n== Festivals ==\n\n=== The Lantern Festival ===\n[[File:Lantern Festival (Chinese characters).svg|left|thumb|Words of \"Lantern festival\" in Chinese characters]]\nThe [[Lantern Festival]](Chinese: \u5143\u5bb5\u8282) is a time for everyone to be with their families. The three-day show, Da Shuhua performs around the [[Lunar New Year]] to celebrate the Lantern Festival in Nuanquan. The Lantern Festival is an ancient festival and usually celebrated on the fifteenth day of the first lunar month. Although it occurs two weeks after the [[Spring Festival - China|Spring Festival]], it is a popular time of the year as it marks the end of the traditional Chinese New Year celebration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Alina|date=Jan-Mar 2017|title=The Lantern Festival|url=|journal=Skipping Stones|volume=|pages=15|via=}}</ref> During the Lantern Festival, local residents gather at the Tree Flower square, in the center of Nuanquan town, for Da Shuhua. On the Lantern Festival, the celebrations of Nuanquan Town start in the morning of the day and continue late into the midnight.<ref name=\":5\" /> Da Shuhua is a way of expressing good wishes that local people prayed for happiness, health and prosperity in the new year. In other places of China, people hung red lanterns outside their windows, eat [[Tangyuan (food)|yuanxiao]](Chinese\uff1a\u5143\u5bb5)and shoot off [[firecracker]]s to celebrate the Lantern Festival.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/sunday/2013-02/24/content_16251429.htm|title=Bright sparks|last=|first=|date=24 Feb 2013|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== The Dragon Boat Festival ===\nDa Shuhua marks the start of the [[Dragon Boat Festival]] (Chinese:\u7aef\u5348\u8282).<ref name=\":4\" /> The Dragon Boat Festival occurs on the fifth day of May of the lunar year, which is a [[Public holidays in China|public holiday in China]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Muxue\"Snow\"|date=Apr-Jun 2018|title=Dragon Boat Festival|url=http://go.galegroup.com.ezproxy1.library.usyd.edu.au/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA535236050&v=2.1&u=usyd&it=r&p=ITOF&sw=w|journal=Skipping Stones|volume=|pages=24|via=}}</ref> The performers of Da Shuhua will start working on the Dragon Boat Festival and every weekend of the second half of the year until the end of the Lantern Festival which marks the end of the Spring Festival. Eating [[zongzi]] (sticky rice dumpling) and racing [[dragon boat]]s are also the traditional activities that people used to celebrate the festival.\n\n== Artists ==\n\n=== Wang De ===\nWang De, who is the lead performer of Da Shuhua in China. Wang was born in Nuanquan, in nineteen sixty-four. As one of the inheritors of Da Shuhua, Wang learned it from his father when he was young. Wang earns 300 [[Yuan (currency)|yuan]] for each show and works on the weekend during the second half of the year and the Spring Festival. The Lantern Festival is the busiest time of the year for Wang. For the rest of the time, Wang grows [[corn]]. Wang has two sons and he passes his skills to his younger son, who was born in nineteen ninety-seven.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201902/21/WS5c6de8e1a3106c65c34ea74f_2.html|title=Molten iron fireworks shows add sparkle to town in Hebei|last=|first=|date=21Feb 2019|work=China Daily|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Sui Jianguo ===\nSui is a 14th generation blacksmith in Nuanquan. He has been performing the art for 25 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/chinese-year-fireworks-dangerous-witness/story?id=36792195|title=Chinese New Year Fireworks So Dangerous That Only a Few Get to Witness|last=Yiu|first=Karson|date=8 Feb 2016|work=ABC News|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Yu Zhangliang ===\nYu is the artist from Nuanquan who took part in the \u201cStory of Yanxi Palace\u201d and performed Da Shuhua in the series.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chinese paper cutting]]\n*[[Story of Yanxi Palace]]\n*[[Yu County, Hebei|Yuxian County]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Chinese New Year|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Festivals in China]]\n[[Category:Lantern Festival]]\n[[Category:Culture in Hebei]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dashuhua"}
